{
  "doc_id": "8376",
  "text": "For the direct diagnosis of atrophic gastritis and intestinal metaplasia, histologic observation from biopsy specimens obtained by endoscopy is the gold standard method. However, there are other methods that are noninvasive and low in cost that seem more suited for mass screening detection of these lesions. In fact, the serologic markers, serum pepsinogen (PG) levels and Helicobacter pylori CagA antibodies (CagA-ab) status, have both been evaluated as screening criteria for the detection of atrophic gastritis in several studies [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . Other markers such as human genetic polymorphisms within the cytokine genes interleukin (IL)-1 and IL-10 have been associated with an increased risk for gastric cancer, probably due to the induction of a hypochlorhydric and atrophic response to H. pylori infection, with atrophic and metaplastic changes in the gastric mucosa [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] . Furthermore, the combination of bacterial pathogenicity (cagA+ and vacA s1) and host genetic factors (IL-1 gene polymorphisms) has been associated with severe histologic changes in the gastric mucosa [CITATION_14] .",
